# Define a function that uses keyword arguments
def greet(name, greeting="Hello"):
    message = f"{greeting}, {name}!"
    return message


# Call the function using keyword arguments
result1 = greet(name="Alice")
result2 = greet(name="Bob", greeting="Hi")

# Print the results
print(result1)
print(result2)


# We define a function called greet with two parameters: name and greeting. The greeting parameter has a default value of "Hello."

# Inside the function, we use these parameters to construct a greeting message, which is stored in the message variable.

# We return the message from the function.

# We call the greet function using keyword arguments:

# In the first call, we provide the name parameter using the keyword argument name="Alice". We omit the greeting argument, so the default "Hello" is used.
# In the second call, we provide both the name and greeting parameters using keyword arguments.
# We print the results of the function calls.
